```go
func makeRetryHandler(maxRetries int, onExhausted func()) func() {
    attempts := 0
    return func() {
        attempts++
        fmt.Printf("attempt %d\n", attempts)
        if attempts >= maxRetries {
            onExhausted()
        }
    }
}

func main() {
    handle := makeRetryHandler(3, func() { fmt.Println("giving up") })
    for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
        handle()
    }
}
// Output:
// attempt 1
// attempt 2
// attempt 3
// giving up
// attempt 4
// giving up
// attempt 5
// giving up
```

statement:
The classic closure-in-loop bug. Explain what this code prints and why, then fix it:

```go
funcs := make([]func(), 3)
for i := 0; i < 3; i++ {
    funcs[i] = func() { fmt.Println(i) }
}
for _, f := range funcs {
    f()
}
```

solution:
**What it prints:** `3 3 3`

**Why:** All three closures capture the *same* `i` variable (not a copy of its value at the time the closure was created). The first loop runs to completion, leaving `i = 3`. When the closures are called in the second loop, all three read the same `i`, which is now `3`.

**Fix:** Pass `i` as a function argument to create a new copy per iteration:

```go
funcs := make([]func(), 3)
for i := 0; i < 3; i++ {
    i := i  // create a new variable scoped to this iteration
    funcs[i] = func() { fmt.Println(i) }
}
```

Or use a parameter:

```go
for i := 0; i < 3; i++ {
    funcs[i] = func(n int) func() {
        return func() { fmt.Println(n) }
    }(i)
}
```
